Yeah and what kinds of worlds have you made with it Usrbinperl, ones with little story and content I take it.  Yeah most anyone can figure out enuff of the toolset to make a &quot;Basic&quot; game.  But if you want to delve into the good stuff and actually make your game interesting you will have a heck of a lot of time doing it.  I spent DAYS trying to figure out how to script properly, and every time I thought I almost had it down something would go wrong Causing me to scrap everything I had done (I quickly learned to make multiple copies of my work as I went).<br>
<br>
It's been a little bit since I played NWN but when I was playing it, EVERY and I mean EVERY player made map I saw flat out sucked.<br>
<br>
Let me give you an idea of the type of stuff I wanted to script but decided wasn't worth 5 weeks   more time to figure out.  I had a detailed story planned for a 1 person adventure.  At the beginning of this adventure the player started by coming down a road and was greeted by a NPC who chats with you because your late.  You soon discover your a mercenary hired to protect a caravan traveling to the Port city of Arison.  JUST in the first part of the game I wanted to have some scripting were the NPC's actually guided you and did stuff instead of standing stationary and having one liner fraises when you talked to them I even worked out personalities for them.  At one part of the beginning I was trying to rig it so you would go to walk up to the caravan masters tent and hear talking coming from the other side of the door and was gong to rig that so the talking would be coming from a few different invisible sources so that your character would auto look and turn its head at the invisible objects as if focusing on each voice.  Not to mention after the talking the door which had been locked would open a dwarf would appear tell you to get out of his way and walk by allowing you to go in and see the caravan master.  Once in there the Caravan master would be sitting in a chair and you would talk to him and in mid conversation he would stand up walk across the room to a map and &quot;Motion&quot; for you to come over to him.  There you would talk some more.  I wont even go into plans I had to make certain NPC's go with you on various quests at different times and do certain key tasks.<br>
<br>
Heck that's only a FRACTION of what I wanted to do.  But do you have any idea how tuff it is to script that whole 5 minutes of in game time?  All of that a player can get through in about 5 minutes but takes so much complex scripting that I looked at what I WANTED to do and how much work it would take to do and said to heck with it.<br>
<br>
Ohh and my conversations weren't these one liner pieces of crap I've usually seen, they were complex with scripting for intelligence checks persuasion checks and a few others.  My conversation for each and every NPC were as detailed if not more so then the ones that came with the never winter nights pre made game.<br>
<br>
So YES Usrbinperl the toolset is easy if you want to design a map toss some monsters in it and let players go through it slaughtering for no reason and getting weapons from chests but to me that's a waste of time with no creativity.  If you want to do cool stuff and make a REAL world with the toolset your in for a LONG LONG LONG LONG lesson in scripting and BIG, I mean BIGGER then everquest time investment.<br>
<br>
I even started opening the main game files and maps that came with the scenarios to get ideas from the game makers scripting and things they did.  HOLY cow there is a lot of scripting in that.  I started Copying pasting scripting and using scripting from the NWN game itself for my own creations but even when doing this you had to make multiple changes to the scripting that you took which made things just as complex if not more so.<br>
<br>
NO thanks.  The game was a good idea but the toolset is to much a pain to use if you ever plan to do anything &quot;complex&quot;.<br>
<br>
So let me ask you Usrbinperl, in your own words &quot;what the hell is YOUR problem?  If you couldn't figure out how to script a detailed game worthy of being on par with the one that came with the game.............<br>
